Additionally, when this can't lock the mutex because it is poisoned this just skips the whole function. There is almost no right way to handle a poisoned mutex except panic.
`Mutex::new` is const. You can skip the `OnceLock` and directly call `Mutex::new(None)` here
There are a few duplicate imports here where both a module and a type from the module are imported simultaneously. That can be a little confusing later.

The @ syntax is deprecated in 0.20 (which you don't use yet). See https://gtk-rs.org/blog/2024/07/17/new-release.html#new-syntax-for-glibclone-and-glibclosure

You can then do
```
#[weak(rename_to = app)]
self
#[upgrade_or]
glib::ControlFlow::Break
```
It's of course somewhat a preference but I would implement private methods on the private, not the public type. Then you don't need to change visibility of your fields either.
